# Persistence

Lives under `infrastructure/persistence`. Keeps JPA fully isolated from the domain.

## Three building blocks

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `JpaUserEntity` | JPA-annotated table mapping. A persistence detail, **not** the domain model. |
| `JpaUserRepository` | Implements the domain `UserRepository` port; uses Spring Data internally. |
| `UserMapper` | Converts `JpaUserEntity` ⇄ domain `User`. |

## Rules

- **Never** annotate domain models with `@Entity`. Persistence uses separate `Jpa*Entity` classes.
- The domain `UserRepository` interface (port) lives in `domain/repository`; its implementation
  lives here and returns **domain models**, mapping via the mapper.
- A Spring Data interface (`*JpaCrudRepository extends JpaRepository`) may be used as an internal
  collaborator, but the port implementation is what the rest of the app depends on.

```java
// domain port -> infra implementation that maps to/from domain
@Repository
public class JpaUserRepository implements UserRepository {
    private final UserJpaCrudRepository crud;   // Spring Data, internal
    private final UserMapper mapper;

    @Override
    public Optional<User> findByEmail(Email email) {
        return crud.findByEmail(email.value()).map(mapper::toDomain);
    }

    @Override
    public User save(User user) {
        return mapper.toDomain(crud.save(mapper.toEntity(user)));
    }
}
```

## Conventions

- Table/column names: `snake_case`. Class names: `Jpa{Aggregate}Entity`.
- Use schema migrations (Flyway/Liquibase) under `resources/db/migration`; do not rely on
  `hibernate.ddl-auto=update` in production.
- Keep queries close to the repository implementation; prefer derived queries or `@Query`
  over scattering raw SQL across the codebase.
